1
00:00:01,601 --> 00:00:03,694
<i>[Man Narrating]
In the criminal justice system...</i>

2
00:00:03,770 --> 00:00:07,137
<i>all defendants are innocent
until proven guilty,</i>

3
00:00:07,207 --> 00:00:11,576
<i>either by confession,
plea bargain or trial byjury.</i>

4
00:00:11,644 --> 00:00:13,578
<i>This is one of those trials.</i>

5
00:00:16,816 --> 00:00:18,807
She was in love with him.

6
00:00:20,120 --> 00:00:23,612
I tried to warn her.
All clichés are true.

7
00:00:24,624 --> 00:00:27,821
But naiveté shouldn't be
a death sentence.

8
00:00:29,062 --> 00:00:34,329
Everybody in this office knows that
Kurt Lascher murdered my daughter.

9
00:00:34,401 --> 00:00:38,030
- You've known for 19 months.
- Unfortunately, Mrs. Blaylock,

10
00:00:38,104 --> 00:00:40,902
knowing and proving
are very different things.

11
00:00:41,975 --> 00:00:45,775
- Her blood-
- Was in the car, but that's inadmissible.

12
00:00:45,845 --> 00:00:48,473
You know that.
It was contaminated.

13
00:00:48,548 --> 00:00:50,482
So you're saying what?

14
00:00:50,550 --> 00:00:53,747
A murderer gets to walk free
just because he's famous?

15
00:00:53,820 --> 00:00:57,483
No, I'm saying it's very difficult to
convict a murderer if there's no evidence.

16
00:00:57,557 --> 00:01:02,153
Well, that's why I'm here-
evidence.

17
00:01:02,228 --> 00:01:05,789
I found this in her trench coat pocket.
It's an obstetrician's card.

18
00:01:05,865 --> 00:01:09,062
There's a date on the back.
It's for the day before she disappeared.

19
00:01:10,136 --> 00:01:13,503
This is great.
We'll look into it.

20
00:01:16,776 --> 00:01:19,176
Yeah. It's not right.

21
00:01:20,647 --> 00:01:23,081
I mean, can you stand there
and tell me that this is right?

22
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:26,448
No.

23
00:01:26,519 --> 00:01:29,181
No, I can't.

24
00:01:35,095 --> 00:01:37,188
[Moaning]

25
00:01:38,832 --> 00:01:42,962
- [Ringing]
- [Moaning Continues]

26
00:01:45,004 --> 00:01:46,699
[Ringing Continues]

27
00:01:53,379 --> 00:01:56,109
What?

28
00:01:56,182 --> 00:02:00,949
What time?
Listen, I have an 11:00 rehearsal.

29
00:02:01,955 --> 00:02:05,254
All right. All right.
I'll have Roberto pick you up on the way.

30
00:02:05,325 --> 00:02:08,522
And, Peter, you were supposed
to make this go away.

31
00:02:08,595 --> 00:02:10,586
Remember that part?

32
00:02:12,765 --> 00:02:14,756
[Phone Beeps Off]

33
00:02:15,768 --> 00:02:20,137
[Sighs] Who was that? My lawyer.

34
00:02:20,206 --> 00:02:22,674
A little late, don't you think?
Uh-huh.

35
00:02:22,742 --> 00:02:24,733
He just got a phone call.

36
00:02:26,045 --> 00:02:28,070
I have to surrender in the morning.

37
00:02:30,283 --> 00:02:32,342
Surrender to who?

38
00:02:32,418 --> 00:02:34,352
Why?

39
00:02:35,488 --> 00:02:39,015
The police.
They think I killed Dede Blaylock.

40
00:02:42,395 --> 00:02:45,091
It's a different prosecutor-
a broad with a hair up her ass.

41
00:02:45,165 --> 00:02:48,396
- Just handle it.
- Oh, that bitch! We agreed.

42
00:02:48,468 --> 00:02:51,028
<i>- Absolutely no press.
- [People Chattering]</i>

43
00:02:54,774 --> 00:02:57,572
<i>Back up. Give 'em some room.
Give 'em some room. Back up.</i>

44
00:02:58,912 --> 00:03:02,245
Give 'em some room. Give 'em some
room to get out. What happened?

45
00:03:05,251 --> 00:03:09,085
<i>- Thank you.
- [Woman] How well did you know her, sir?</i>

46
00:03:09,155 --> 00:03:11,214
Can you just please let us through?

47
00:03:11,291 --> 00:03:14,385
Kurt, you know I would never
have agreed to this perp walk.

48
00:03:14,460 --> 00:03:16,519
Shut up, Peter.
She didn't call 'em.

49
00:03:17,530 --> 00:03:19,896
<i>I did. [Man] Did you kill
your girlfriend, Mr. Lascher?</i>

50
00:03:19,966 --> 00:03:22,594
Did you kill your girlfriend?

51
00:03:22,669 --> 00:03:25,661
<i>[Chattering Continues]</i>

52
00:03:30,643 --> 00:03:32,634
<i>[Man] Please, sir. Thank you.</i>

53
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:26,293
<i>Docket 101604, People of the State
of New York versus Kurt Lascher.</i>

54
00:04:26,366 --> 00:04:28,334
<i>Charge is murder in the second degree.</i>

55
00:04:28,401 --> 00:04:31,928
- How do you plead, Mr. Lascher?
- Absolutely not guilty.

56
00:04:32,005 --> 00:04:34,166
<i>[Judge] Save the rewrites
for the paying customers.</i>

57
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:36,367
A simple declarative "not guilty"
is incredibly sufficient.

58
00:04:36,442 --> 00:04:38,967
- Thank you, Your Honor.
- People on bail. Ms. Gaffney?

59
00:04:39,045 --> 00:04:43,141
It's a murder, Your Honor.
The defendant has a nine-figure net worth.

60
00:04:43,216 --> 00:04:45,707
<i>He has a Gulfstream jet that can
take him out of this country at will.</i>

61
00:04:45,785 --> 00:04:48,811
<i>We ask for remand given that he is
the living definition of a flight risk.</i>

62
00:04:48,888 --> 00:04:51,288
<i>Ray Charles could have
seen that, counselor.</i>

63
00:04:51,357 --> 00:04:53,689
However, I'm loathe to remand
someone when there's no body.

64
00:04:53,760 --> 00:04:59,255
<i>But I can make it expensive. Bail is
set at five million dollars. Short date.</i>

65
00:04:59,332 --> 00:05:02,790
- What?
- And Mr. Lascher will surrender his passport.

66
00:05:03,870 --> 00:05:06,566
<i>- [Man] Did you kill your girlfriend, Mr. Lascher?
- Did you kill your girlfriend?</i>

67
00:05:06,639 --> 00:05:08,903
<i>[Branch]
Clearly a defendant who is terrified...</i>

68
00:05:08,975 --> 00:05:11,739
at the prospect of dealing
with the criminal justice system.

69
00:05:11,811 --> 00:05:16,578
The man is custom-tailored scum,
Arthur. He's a producer, Jack.

70
00:05:16,649 --> 00:05:19,413
<i>And the reason I had you
hand this case offlast year...</i>

71
00:05:19,485 --> 00:05:22,386
is because I didn't see how a jury
would convict this guy...

72
00:05:22,455 --> 00:05:25,322
without the blood evidence,
not to mention without the body,

73
00:05:25,391 --> 00:05:29,350
and I didn't want my executive assistant
to lose a celebrity case at trial.

74
00:05:29,429 --> 00:05:31,363
Why would I want one of
my bureau chiefs?

75
00:05:31,431 --> 00:05:35,993
<i>Because it's a very strong circumstantial
case, and we know he did it.</i>

76
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:37,934
Come on, Tracey.
Ajury won't know that.

77
00:05:38,004 --> 00:05:42,532
<i>Are you absolutely certain there's
no way we can get the blood in?</i>

78
00:05:42,608 --> 00:05:45,304
The people at the lab told me categorically
that Dede Blaylock's blood...

79
00:05:45,378 --> 00:05:47,573
was in the rental car,

80
00:05:47,647 --> 00:05:51,515
but couldn't swear under oath to
a reasonable degree of scientific certainty.

81
00:05:51,584 --> 00:05:53,518
Exactly what they said
a year and a half ago.

82
00:05:53,586 --> 00:05:55,850
It's circumstantial,
but the circumstances are compelling.

83
00:05:55,922 --> 00:05:58,186
<i>[Kibre] Another circumstance:
Her mother found...</i>

84
00:05:58,257 --> 00:06:01,454
a gynecologist's business card
in one of her coats.

85
00:06:01,527 --> 00:06:04,018
The doctor will testify that
Dede Blaylock was pregnant.

86
00:06:04,097 --> 00:06:07,533
Will this doctor testify that
Kurt Lascher was the father?

87
00:06:12,739 --> 00:06:16,436
[Sighs] Well, let's see if
we can even indict this jerk.

88
00:06:17,443 --> 00:06:20,469
Has he indicated he wants
to testify before the grand jury?

89
00:06:20,546 --> 00:06:23,413
Kelly gave Behrens
a 19050 at the arraignment.

90
00:06:23,483 --> 00:06:26,008
My guess- Behrens will say
that Lascher is going to.

91
00:06:26,085 --> 00:06:28,076
<i>I'll notice him to appear
- [Branch] He'll miss the date.</i>

92
00:06:28,154 --> 00:06:30,918
You'll reschedule. Lascher'll be sick.
You'll get the indictment.

93
00:06:30,990 --> 00:06:34,221
<i>Which sets up a motion to dismiss
for failure to give Lascher...</i>

94
00:06:34,293 --> 00:06:37,228
an adequate opportunity
to testify before the G.J.

95
00:06:37,296 --> 00:06:39,230
A case this big,
some judges might give it to them.

96
00:06:39,298 --> 00:06:42,062
- It's just delaying the inevitable.
- Since when is anything...

97
00:06:42,135 --> 00:06:44,603
inevitable with the law?

98
00:06:45,671 --> 00:06:47,696
<i>[Woman] Second line in.
Wanda, Carrie. [Piano]</i>

99
00:06:47,774 --> 00:06:50,538
Delay? That's it? Delay?

100
00:06:50,610 --> 00:06:55,240
Kurt, delay is
a guilty man's best friend.

101
00:06:55,314 --> 00:06:57,874
Don't you ever sit in judgment of me.

102
00:06:57,950 --> 00:07:01,113
It's not my job. I'm your lawyer.
You ask, and I'll answer.

103
00:07:01,187 --> 00:07:03,451
<i>[Man]
Take five, people!</i>

104
00:07:04,457 --> 00:07:06,550
<i>[Ends]</i>

105
00:07:06,626 --> 00:07:08,958
Why did the little bitch get pregnant?

106
00:07:09,028 --> 00:07:10,962
[Scoffs]

107
00:07:12,064 --> 00:07:15,465
Slate myself?
Dede Blaylock.

108
00:07:15,535 --> 00:07:19,471
<i>She was just chasing a dream.
Once Lascher started sniffing around-</i>

109
00:07:19,539 --> 00:07:23,305
- She was in love. He was in lust.
- Tracey Kibre's got a hard-on for Lascher.

110
00:07:23,376 --> 00:07:25,674
Kibre?
I never had a case with her.

111
00:07:25,745 --> 00:07:27,679
Yeah, she's tough, smart.

112
00:07:27,747 --> 00:07:30,716
Hates to lose. I'm tellin' ya,
I wouldn't want her after my ass.

113
00:07:30,783 --> 00:07:32,808
<i>I would have kept my mouth shut
- [Salazar] You seen enough?</i>

114
00:07:32,885 --> 00:07:36,753
Yeah.
Anyway, it's not our problem.

115
00:07:36,823 --> 00:07:38,848
Oh?
What is our problem?

116
00:07:38,925 --> 00:07:41,223
To make sure Kibre's got
all the evidence that's there,

117
00:07:41,294 --> 00:07:45,128
reinterview everybody the homicide detectives
talked to, go over all the paperwork.

118
00:07:45,198 --> 00:07:48,827
Yeah, see if the precinct guys
screwed up. Yeah, it happens.

119
00:07:49,936 --> 00:07:54,339
You know, Lennie, I was a precinct
detective before I got shot five times.

120
00:07:54,407 --> 00:07:56,500
If it wasn't for this squad,
I'd be on permanent disability.

121
00:07:56,576 --> 00:07:59,875
- I'd be retired.
- So don't kick a gift horse in the mouth.

122
00:07:59,946 --> 00:08:02,312
Well, it helps pay the alimony.
So who's up first?

123
00:08:02,381 --> 00:08:05,873
Vic's roommate,
Karen Masters.

124
00:08:07,186 --> 00:08:10,644
You have any idea how many sessions
it took for me to get through this?

125
00:08:10,723 --> 00:08:14,159
Excuse me?
With my shrink.

126
00:08:14,227 --> 00:08:18,596
Your pregnant best friend goes out
to dinner, and she never comes back.

127
00:08:18,664 --> 00:08:23,101
Some new evidence has come up.
And?

128
00:08:23,169 --> 00:08:26,104
The D.A.' s going to the grand jury.
They'd like you to testify.

129
00:08:26,172 --> 00:08:29,369
<i>Whoa. Nobody ever said
anything about testifying.</i>

130
00:08:29,442 --> 00:08:33,902
- Wait a minute. Are you an actress?
- Only when I'm not being a paralegal.

131
00:08:33,980 --> 00:08:37,381
I've seen you in a commercial.
You saw my Land Rover?

132
00:08:37,450 --> 00:08:41,181
I knew it was some kind of car.
Which one- But you were great.

133
00:08:41,254 --> 00:08:45,088
You want to see my reel?
I'm just kidding.

134
00:08:45,157 --> 00:08:49,491
<i>I know you're nervous about testifying,
but grandjury testimony is sealed.</i>

135
00:08:49,562 --> 00:08:51,530
Nobody in the business
will ever find out.

136
00:08:51,597 --> 00:08:53,588
Kurt Lascher will.

137
00:08:55,368 --> 00:08:57,302
I'm gonna have to think about this.

138
00:09:02,842 --> 00:09:06,437
You guessin' she's an actress-
That's a no-brainer.

139
00:09:06,512 --> 00:09:08,776
You saw her damn commercial,
and you remembered her face?

140
00:09:08,848 --> 00:09:12,147
No, I got TiVo. You push the magic button,
there's no commercials.

141
00:09:13,553 --> 00:09:16,681
Who's next? Maître d' of the
restaurant where they ate.

142
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:22,887
<i>And Lascher's been a regular here
how long?</i>

143
00:09:22,962 --> 00:09:26,693
Since you were walking a beat.
Twice a week, sometimes more.

144
00:09:26,766 --> 00:09:31,032
What about women?
Two a week, sometimes more.

145
00:09:31,103 --> 00:09:35,335
- What about this woman?
- I figured this was about Dede Blaylock.

146
00:09:35,408 --> 00:09:37,342
Nice girl.

147
00:09:37,410 --> 00:09:40,937
Fell in love with Lascher.
Not a smart thing to do.

148
00:09:41,013 --> 00:09:45,006
- So she came in more than once?
- Once a week for three or four months.

149
00:09:45,084 --> 00:09:48,918
<i>She used to tell me
this was their place. Delusional.</i>

150
00:09:48,988 --> 00:09:51,286
<i>The Homicide guys came around
two or three times...</i>

151
00:09:51,357 --> 00:09:54,019
<i>after she disappeared,
but then nothing happened.</i>

152
00:09:54,093 --> 00:09:57,256
- What's going on?
- The D.A.' s taking this to the grand jury.

153
00:09:57,330 --> 00:10:00,322
- You're going to have to testify.
- Oh, great.

154
00:10:00,399 --> 00:10:03,232
Why don't you take us through
what happened the last time she was here?

155
00:10:03,302 --> 00:10:06,169
The night she disappeared?
Yeah, the night she disappeared.

156
00:10:06,238 --> 00:10:09,696
Well, they seemed happy.
Lascher had a couple of vodkas,

157
00:10:09,775 --> 00:10:12,471
and then he ordered
a magnum of Cristal.

158
00:10:12,545 --> 00:10:14,479
She said they had
something to celebrate.

159
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:17,981
They had a magnum?
They drink the whole thing?

160
00:10:18,050 --> 00:10:21,645
Well, she just sipped at one glass,
but he turned it into a dead soldier.

161
00:10:21,721 --> 00:10:24,690
He get smashed?
Lascher never got smashed.

162
00:10:24,757 --> 00:10:28,056
<i>Check that.
He never looked smashed.</i>

163
00:10:29,061 --> 00:10:31,894
- He did some coke in the men's room.
- Oh? How do you know that?

164
00:10:31,964 --> 00:10:35,627
Because he's been doing coke in the
men's room ever since I've been here.

165
00:10:35,701 --> 00:10:38,693
Anyway, he came back to the table...

166
00:10:38,771 --> 00:10:41,331
and sent his chauffeur home,

167
00:10:41,407 --> 00:10:43,500
then tells me to get him a rental car.

168
00:10:43,576 --> 00:10:46,704
- He do that often?
- Try never.

169
00:10:46,779 --> 00:10:48,940
<i>Never is an absolute.</i>

170
00:10:49,015 --> 00:10:51,313
He'll testify to never? In the
12 years he's been working there,

171
00:10:51,384 --> 00:10:54,080
he said he never saw Lascher
send his driver home.

172
00:10:54,153 --> 00:10:56,178
He didn't even know
Lascher had a license.

173
00:10:56,255 --> 00:11:00,248
And Dede just had the one glass of
champagne? Yeah. She didn't even finish that.

174
00:11:00,326 --> 00:11:02,453
I mean, she sure acted like
she had a bun in the oven.

175
00:11:02,528 --> 00:11:05,224
<i>Based on the fact that Lascher
made his last child support payment...</i>

176
00:11:05,297 --> 00:11:07,390
for his illegitimate son
three months ago-

177
00:11:07,466 --> 00:11:10,902
<i>Seventeen and a half percent of
his annual income for the last 18 years.</i>

178
00:11:10,970 --> 00:11:14,167
A pregnancy would probably
really piss him off.

179
00:11:14,240 --> 00:11:17,266
<i>- No wonder he drank the whole magnum.
- [Kibre] I'm probably gonna be able to get...</i>

180
00:11:17,343 --> 00:11:21,177
the grand jury to indict, but when we go to
trial, we're gonna need a lot more to convict.

181
00:11:21,247 --> 00:11:23,738
I want you to enhance the case.

182
00:11:23,816 --> 00:11:27,843
<i>And welcome to the squad, Detective.
You're one ofJack McCoy's favorite cops.</i>

183
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:30,889
Thanks. It's better than hanging out
at the O.T.B.

184
00:11:35,695 --> 00:11:39,722
- You're really worried.
- I'm always worried.

185
00:11:43,269 --> 00:11:45,703
<i>They were dating for about six
or seven months.</i>

186
00:11:47,006 --> 00:11:50,772
I'm not quite sure how long they were going out,
because she didn't tell me when they first got together.

187
00:11:50,843 --> 00:11:53,573
- And why was that?
- It was Kurt Lascher.

188
00:11:53,646 --> 00:11:57,582
He's notorious.
Notorious. For what?

189
00:11:58,951 --> 00:12:01,078
<i>[Karen]
Okay. How's this?</i>

190
00:12:01,153 --> 00:12:04,179
<i>He's also 33 years older than Dede.</i>

191
00:12:05,624 --> 00:12:08,457
I knew she was gonna get hurt.
I didn't think she was gonna get killed.

192
00:12:11,230 --> 00:12:13,562
What did you say to her
when she told you she was pregnant?

193
00:12:13,632 --> 00:12:16,260
That I would go with her
for the abortion.

194
00:12:16,335 --> 00:12:19,463
<i>And what was her response?
She said she was having the baby.</i>

195
00:12:19,538 --> 00:12:23,167
- Was she upset?
- She was ecstatic.

196
00:12:23,242 --> 00:12:27,269
She said they'd get married,
and... I lost it.

197
00:12:27,346 --> 00:12:30,076
I told her she was kidding herself.

198
00:12:30,149 --> 00:12:34,176
<i>We started fighting,
yelling at each other.</i>

199
00:12:34,253 --> 00:12:36,915
I left.

200
00:12:36,989 --> 00:12:39,184
I never saw her again.

201
00:12:39,258 --> 00:12:42,591
<i>Thank you, Karen. Questions?</i>

202
00:12:42,661 --> 00:12:44,424
Uh-
[Clears Throat]

203
00:12:44,497 --> 00:12:47,022
- Mr. Duzshinsky?
- Did she say...

204
00:12:47,099 --> 00:12:49,090
whether she had told Lascher...

205
00:12:49,168 --> 00:12:51,261
how many other men
she had slept with?

206
00:12:51,337 --> 00:12:53,999
<i>What? In her life?</i>

207
00:12:54,073 --> 00:12:56,371
<i>No, no.
The week she disappeared.</i>

208
00:12:56,442 --> 00:12:59,639
- She wasn't sleeping with anyone else.
- Oh, you know?

209
00:12:59,712 --> 00:13:02,613
What, you are psychic too?
She's an actress.

210
00:13:10,222 --> 00:13:13,089
No wonder Russians hate jury trials.

211
00:13:13,159 --> 00:13:16,993
Can you imagine 12 Duzshinskys
trying to reach a unanimous verdict?

212
00:13:17,062 --> 00:13:19,462
<i>[Door Opens]
Here it is.</i>

213
00:13:21,901 --> 00:13:23,892
Thank you.

214
00:13:26,839 --> 00:13:28,830
Murder two.

215
00:13:33,946 --> 00:13:36,574
You wanted enhancement?
I got you enhancement.

216
00:13:36,649 --> 00:13:40,210
It's all irrelevant and totally inadmissible,
but it certainly enhances your perspective.

217
00:13:40,286 --> 00:13:44,086
